You're not alone having trouble getting far with
healers. In my current logfile's 206 healer
attempts, I've made it exactly once as far as DLVL
13, and a cockatrice corpse got me there.

I think you are way underestimating healers, though,
when you call them &quot;lame&quot;.

It takes pretty incredibly bad luck to _prevent_ a
healer from doing both Sokoban and Mines Town at
XL:1, and thus ending up with a naked AC usually
_better than_ AC:1, what with having extra money to
donate past the first easy 9 AC improvement points.

You have going for you:

1) a fistfull of healing potions to instantly bring
your HP up to 25 or more

2) the ability to cast Healing and Extra Healing on
your pets _and_ you

3) the stethoscope to keep constant track of your
pets' health

4) at least a few /Sleep charges to avoid gaining XP
in the tightest situations

5) a big wad of zorkmids with which to jump start
credit cloning

6) you start the game with the most immediately
important intrinsic, poison resistance.

Really, really obsess about zorkmids, because you
plan to show up at the Mines town altar richer than
Croesus and still at XL:1, letting you buy
protection at 400z a pop.

So even a few extra zorkmids make for an extra
donation attempt: with the help of a couple of
lucre-rich bones files, I once got to make over 50
donation attempts in Mines Town alone, ending up
with a naked AC:-4 with no help from prayers.

Manage your pets well (and accumulate several buff
ones), and you'll thrive to the point where you've
accumulated enchanted armor and a really good AC,
just on Mines levels death drops.

The one thing I've found _really_ important is not
to treat the protection racket like a race, but
instead like a very self-assured stroll where you
_know_ your skill managing your pets, and all the
resources a healer has to assist that, keeps all
your problems small.

Let your pets BUC-test _everything_, and try on all
uncursed armor, there are some really lously armor
types that look a lot better at +5 enchantment when
you find them on the floor.

Take time to explore every level thoroughly for
objects and treasure and sessile monsters.

Find a few shops to bankrupt, and credit clone your
way to riches and a wealth of objects, some even
useful.

Get a pick-axe, then go back to find and empty every
vault you heard on the way down.

Get a few potions of object detection from nymphs
unlucky enough to approach your pets or find you on
Sokoban, and check each level for buried gold and
gems.

Let your pets clean out the Sokoban treasure zoo for
you so you can avoid unwanted XPs.

You're a spellcaster, so rubblize the Oracle level
statues looking for spellbooks.

Once you've gotten good AC in Mines Town, level up
_very slowly_ to keep down the monster HD levels you
and more importantly your pets must face.

Don't gain an XL until you have all of: the AC,
intrinsics, spells, and weapons, to face the
monsters gaining it implies.

Eventually, altar camp somewhere for artifacts
and/or more spell books.

Healers are doable, I think, but they're surely an
acquired taste.

After playing healers for a while, and learning to
take advantage of their inherent benefits, though,
all the _other_ classes start to look much harder
than healers are.

That's probably why 30% or so of my logfile
games were played as healers, my default
class.

xanthian.
