We're opposite there, I rarely stick to an altar
for even a dozen turns, though I may return to it
for BUC IDing several times, but I'm constantly on
the hunt for the odd zorkmid.

That 20,000z is not really the big obstacle you make
it out to be. A richest-possible  Mines Town can
contain 16,000z just in shopkeeper's wallets. Find
one more richest-possible shop elsewhere in the main
dungeon in a round trip to Sokoban, and you've got
20,000z already.

More realistically to make up for shopkeeper
shortfalls from their maximum 4,000z, you've got
several vaults, lots of gold death-dropped by the
Mines dwarf population, little stacks of gold
covered in dust bunnies almost everywhere, gold in
the Dungeon and Mines rocks or buried beneath them,
gold in the Sokoban treasure zoo, and on and on.

Getting gold is easy if you aren't running a
footrace as your version of the protection racket,
because at least several monsters killed by your
pets will death-drop gold, too, and the slower you
go, the more such death-drops there will be.

As for managing pets, I find that one of the game's
most interesting aspects. It takes a real lover of
tedium to specialize in cat herding, I suppose.

