I have a pretty set strategy in mind when I start, however I know many
people don't like it because it involves wearing metal armor.*

Upon starting the game, I immediately quaff any b !oEH for HP.  I let
my pet kill off most critters, and make my primary goal obtaining a
mithril armor and other good armors.  Protection racket for me is a
toss-up.  Most of the time I don't bother with it (as I don't like to
unnecessarily risk the lives of my early baby Healers), but if the
sun, Jupiter and Saturn are aligned just so, I may attempt it.  Once I
obtain decent armor (yes, I wear metal armor on a healer), I find that
I don't need to heal myself as frequently as before.  So now I am able
to wear my armor in battle, then remove my armor only (as my heal
success rate with iron shoes/hard hat equipped usually is still very
good), heal myself and my pet back to full, then gear myself back up
for battle.  The use of mithril for my healers is only to survive
early game; I will trade it in for leather once I've gotten my natural
AC fairly low.

As for my weapon, I've primarily used my scalpel (only to advance my
knife for my future weapon, crysknife), however as of late I've taken
a liking to daggers.  I strongly recommend the dagger route over the
scalpel -&gt; crysknife.  While the crysknife is a great weapon, the
scalpel is just too weak to really fight monsters such as leocrattas.
As others have mentioned, the unicorn horn is also another great
alternative.  The only thing not to do, is to try to advance all of
these at once.

If necessary, I will intentionally level drain myself later ingame
after I have obtained the Staff, so I can re-allocate my skill points
that were previously used in unicorn horn or knife.  I find by that
point, gaining my levels back is not an issue at all.

Facing Cyclops: The level beneath Cyclops, I engrave a permanent
Elbereth (or hard-engrave into the floor if I don't have a perm E
method by then), go upstairs, wake up Cyclops, go back downstairs and
duke it out with him.  Sleep works wonders on him as well (which I'll
have to do sans-E on sporkhack, since lorimer the pikachu is the devil
incarnate and made all Quest nemesis ignore Elbereth u_u!!) Once I
have the staff in my hands, the game is pretty much in the bag.

I wish you luck on your quest to play and ascend one of the most
underrated classes possible, the Healer.

-Annie
*Disclaimer: this is just the way I've played my healers.  I am not
claiming it is the best way, but it does work for me.  Please don't
shoot me. :)
